{
  "text": "Once degeneracy is achieved, it should be possible to load the mixture into a 3D optical lattice. Such a lattice provides a very sensitive environment for the detection of Feshbach resonances [CITATION_1] and an ideal platform for molecule formation. 1 G. Many such resonances exist in both limiting regimes of anisotropy. In the low-anisotropy case they are mostly due to bound states with L = 4 or 6. The background scattering length for these resonances is moderately tunable with magnetic field, as seen in Fig. 1 , but is centered around the isotropic scattering length a iso . If necessary, a iso may be selected by choosing an appropriate isotopic combination. In the high-anisotropy case there are narrow resonances suitable for magnetoassociation, with a wide variety of background scattering lengths even for a single interaction potential (or isotopic combination). In this case, careful selection of isotopes may be unnecessary.",
